latestIgtvVideos.title: Pathological Diagnosis of Acne #episode3
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Before we jump on to different treatments and nutritional management for acne, lets talk about diagnosis or which blood tests to do which will help us understand if the acne is due to hormonal imbalance or due to any nutrient deficiency or overdose!

Blood tests/ Pathological diagnosis includes:
- Getting hormonal profile done (which will include your stress hormones, male hormones, DHT, Cortisol & Prolactin) This might vary as per what your experts recommend.
- Lipid Profile
- Thyroid Profile
- CBC, Serum Iron & Ferritin
- Abdominal & Pelvic Ultrasound for PCOS related acne
- Serum B12

Kindly note: Get these tests prescribed from your expert (Nutritionist or Dermotologist) under their guidance only.
.
.

latestIgtvVideos.title: Causes of Acne #episode2
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Acne occurs for various reasons and at various stages and ages. We believe acne is caused by not only one particular reason but it is a 360 degree approach that leads to inflammation like Acne. 

There are many causes that trigger acne, Here are a few explained:

1. Poor Lifestyle: Unhealthy eating habits, increase consumption of alcohol and smoking, sedentary lifestyle, Skipping meals  can all lead to acne.
2. Lack of Nutrition: Not meeting your nutrient requirements that are important for your skin and body. Lack of antioxidants in the diet leads to inflammation like acne.
3. Increase consumption of Fried foods, Dairy, Processed Carbs and Refined Sugars
4. Poor Gut health (which include any gut issues like constipation or bloating that can increase the bad bacteria in intestine leading to acne)
5. Lack of water (Dehydrated skin increases sebun production leading to acne)
6. Hormomal Fluctuations: High levels of Male hormones can increase oil production. Birth control pills, PMS changes, PCOS, Pregnancy and Menopause can also lead to acne
7. Stress: Stress causes hormonal fluctuations and increased sebum production.
8. Using wrong products
.
.

Juicing sounds healthy- but is yours actually helping you?
This simple veggie juice isn’t just a trend- it’s been my constant morning ritual for the past 15 years, and here’s why I swear by it👇🏼

But here’s what most people miss 👇🏼

🥬 Variety is key – A rainbow of vegetables means a wider range of nutrients. Repeating the same combo daily? You might be missing out.

🕐 Timing matters – Drink it within 5 minutes of juicing to avoid nutrient loss.

🚫 Straining isn’t always ideal – Unless you have IBS or gut issues, don’t strain your juice. The fiber is your friend—it feeds your good gut bacteria.

🧠 Juicing isn’t one-size-fits-all – What works for someone else may not work for your unique body, hormones, or health goals.

🥄 Juice ≠ Meal replacement – It’s a supportive add-on, not a substitute for meals or balanced nutrition.

🌿 Functional twist – Done right, your veggie juice can support digestion, reduce inflammation, balance hormones, and leave your skin thanking you.

But it all depends on what your body actually needs.
